arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This collection is organized into five series: Buildings and grounds; Students; Faculty and staff; Subject files; and Unprocessed accessions.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: This collection was processed in winter 2010 by MacKenzie Brigham, DCA Collections Assistant, under the supervision of Susanne Belovari, Archivist for Reference and Collections. Due to the large number of accessions represented in this collection, original order was hard to determine and maintain. Most slides and internegatives were rehoused for preservation purposes. Materials that were found together (ex: materials found in same projector wheel or slide case) were rehoused together in plastic protectors. There was also an attempt to maintain original labels and titles provided by the Office of Publications. New titles were assigned when titles did not exist to begin with or when original titles were not descriptive and inhibited access. Labels assigned by archivist are identified by brackets.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection is composed of photographs, negatives, slides, and digital images of Tufts University from 1908 to 2009. Aside from photographic materials, the collection also contains newspaper clippings, brochures, publications, and press releases. The bulk of the collection consists of images of the Tufts campus as well as its students, faculty, and staff. The collection also captures many aspects of life at Tufts, such as events and locations that define the school, the social and academic life of students, and the professional life of faculty and staff. A large portion of the collection are stock images captured by professional photographers for publications and marketing purposes, although a number of snapshot-style images donated by alums, faculty, and staff are also included.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Office of Publications is one of four departments comprising Tufts Office of Communications. This Office is responsible producing magazines, newsletters, and marketing material for Tufts University. Through design and writing the Office of Publication aims to capture and share the visual and intellectual identity of the University. The Office also offers editorial, design, and project management services for Tufts departments, and maintains external contracts with photographers and design firms.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection contains some restricted material. Restrictions related to specific material are listed in the detailed contents list. This collection may require review before it is available for use. Please contact DCA for further details.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs, slides, and negatives of physical spaces associated with Tufts. The majority of the images were captured between 1967 and 2003, though some are more recent. The majority of the images are stock photographs of buildings on Tufts' Medford campus. While most shots depict the exterior of buildings, some also display interior scenes with and without students. Some images indicate a specific season, with a focus on Tufts' flora, fauna and foliage. Despite a focus on Medford facilities, the series also houses photographs of the Veterinary, Dental and Medical School campuses. Photographs of Boston are also included in this series. A number of images also show new construction and architectural renderings of planned buildings. Materials are both black and white and color.

scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs, slides, and negatives of Tufts University students from 1967 to 1999. Images include stock photography used in publications as well as candid shots of the academic and social lives of students. Shots are taken in a variety of locations, including classrooms, libraries, on campus grounds and around Boston. Some also depict specific students; Medical, Dental, Fletcher. This series contains a number of images used in admissions campaigns for the College of Arts & Sciences, as well as the Fletcher School.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs, slides, and negatives depicting identified Tufts events, departments, activities, and academic subjects. The subjects in this series might overlap with those found in other series, but the content differs. For example, folders labeled "Library" in subject files show students using the library and engaging in library-related activities, whereas those materials labeled "Library" in the Buildings & Grounds series show the physical structure of the library. This series contains a large number of photographs of annual Tufts events, including commencement photographs from 1952 to 2002, and images of Alumni Weekend, Mayoralty, Tuftonia's Day, and Homecoming. There are also photographs from one-time events, like the 1992 World's Fair and groundbreaking ceremonies for campus buildings. Academic subject areas like engineering, chemistry, and medicine also have strong representation. There are also images of select extracurricular activities like Yacht Club, orchestra, and dance.
